l must shut most everything down on raids.  I'm currently building a new machine with a fasters processor, better video card and just a tiny bit more RAM, I will still run about with most things turned off... I still stick on the environment... in other words, running across a zone is like being in a manual transmission automobile being driven by a person who has never seen a car before. <p><img src=http://24.26.194.142/sevsig.gif></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=targonis>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 799<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/23/03 12:41 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: hmm</span><hr size=1> There will always be SOME limiting factor in how fast things happen on a computer.  The one that MOST people run into is not having enough memory.  But a Geforce 2, or any Geforce card with an MX in the name will indicate that your video card is OLD, and just can't handle the ammount of information that needs to be displayed quickly enough.  To be fair, an ATI Radeon 7000 series(which includes the Radeon DDR) is in the same boat.  The Radeon 8500 is also a bit slow by today's standards.  <br>
<br>
Next in the slow category is the Geforce 3 series, which is very outdated, though still faster than a Geforce 4 MX.  Similar in speed to these cards is the Radeon 9000, 9100, and 9200.<br>
<br>
I'd say that a MINIMUM card you should even look at would be a geforce 4 Ti4200, or Radeon 9500 or 9600.  The Radeon 9500 pro, and 9600 pro are roughly the performance of a Geforce 4 Ti4400, perhaps a bit faster.<br>
<br>
On to the performance cards, the Radeon 9700 and later will make EQ run well, as will a Geforce 4 Ti4600 and Ti4800.  Avoid the Geforce FX 5200, it's NOT a performance card.  You get what you pay for is the way these things work.<br>
<br>
Now, I'd be guilty of leaving out a CRITICAL piece of information if I didn't mention that you MUST have a fast enough CPU(processor) in order to properly feed the cards I call the MINIMUM cards to look at.  A Pentium 4 1.7GHz or Athlon XP 1700+ are what should be your minimums to avoid the CPU being your bottleneck with these video cards.<br>
<br>
So, low memory means that even with a top of the line video card and processor, your system will be swapping to the hard drive and you lose performance.  Too low processor power, and the games you want to play will be starved when it comes to calculating what to display, but even with these two things, a slow video card will choke the performance of a game.<br>
<br>
For those who love to know WHY, here's the scoop...<br>
For any 3D game, objects are made up of polygons(basic geometric shapes), and a 3D accelerator(all video cards are these days) will handle most of the calculations on how to display the objects the game wants to display.  Obviously, the more objects to display will mean your video card has a more work to do in order to properly display them.<br>
<br>
Now, when Luclin came out, a few important things happened with EQ.  First, EQ moved a number of things that used to be done by the CPU to be done by the video card(if available).  Hardware support was added for T&amp;L, which stands for Transform and Lighting.  It helps a bit on the rendering, but REQUIRES a Geforce or Radeon video card in order to use the T&amp;L code.  Also, the Luclin character models were a LOT more detailed than the original EQ.  As a result, slower video cards would choke on the increased level of detail since the number of polygons used to display characters went up.  Many people havn't looked, but in the EQ options(the one before you put in your login name and password), there is a way to lower the texture detail.  Even with a video card that has enough power to keep up, if your CPU(processor) isn't able to provide the video card with information, things will still be slow, and running out of system memory will choke the system to prevent your CPU from being able to do it's job.<br>
<br>
My own video card is a Radeon 9500 pro which I picked up when it first came out for $200 US dollars.  Except for AE groups, I can generally leave my details all the way up even on raids.  The exception for this is the Bazaar.  Now, while going to a Radeon 9800 pro or Geforce FX 5800 or 5900 might boost my video performance, the problem with EQ is that it tries to display objects on the other side of walls that you couldn't possibly hope to see.  So even with only 3 characters visible, EQ will throw 100+ character models(remember I have Luclin models turned on too) at my video card, which then will use main system memory(remember my discussion on the AGP apature), which slows things down even more.  So a 256 meg video card is the key to boosting my performance.<br>
<br>
To be honest, EQ isn't worth spending $450 to $500 for a 256 meg video card at this point in time.  I have no idea how intensive EQ 2 or Horizons may be when it comes to this, so I'll just wait until they come out, THEN decide.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 65 Wizard<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
